You have some problems with your javascript. I would recommend avoiding using callbacks, 'then's, AND async/await syntax. It gets very hard to reason about. I don't think all of your async stuff is very clean and I think things might be a bit out of whack.

Try untangling things a bit and structuring your code something like this:
```
    contract.deploy({ data: bytecode }).send({
        from: admin,
        gas: 4712388,
        gasPrice: 100000000000
      }, (error, transactionHash) => {
        console.log(error,transactionHash);      
      }).then(instance=>{
        return instance.methods.newTransact(receiver, 'dob').send({from: sender});
      }).then(receipt => {
        console.log("do something with receipt --> %o", receipt);
........
```
Or if you want to use async/await, like this:
```
    const instance = await contract.deploy({ data: bytecode}).send({
      from: admin,
      gas: 4712388,
      gasPrice: 100000000000
    });
    const result = await instance.methods.newTransact(receiver, 'dob').send({from: sender});
      console.log("something with result --> %o", result);
........
```

> Also, deploy is async so you need to wait until it is finished deploying before you can send transactions. So currently your transaction call will probably try to run before the contract is deployed and this will cause a problem.

